Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:19.380
&gt;&gt; Mari Nakahara: Good
afternoon, everybody.

00:00:19.380 --> 00:00:22.990
On behalf of the Prints and
Photographs Division of the Library

00:00:22.990 --> 00:00:26.650
of Congress and its Center
for Architecture, Design,

00:00:26.650 --> 00:00:31.670
and Engineering, it's my great
pleasure to welcome you all

00:00:31.670 --> 00:00:37.100
to today's lecture, "Tracking
Time: Twin Towers and Motor City,"

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:41.580
by the distinguished American
photographer and documentarian,

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:45.560
Camilo Jose Vergara,
followed by a book signing

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:51.600
of his newly published book,
Detroit Is No Dry Bones.

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:52.900
My name is Mari Nakahara.

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:58.080
I am a curator of architecture,
design, and engineering at the P

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:01.020
and P we call -- Prints
and Photographs Division.

00:01:01.020 --> 00:01:06.440
I have been in this position for
the last one year and nine months.

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:10.690
In comparison with my predecessor,
[inaudible] -- he's there --

00:01:10.690 --> 00:01:16.040
his career is, was 40
years, and he retired April.

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:17.630
I am still a baby.

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:20.530
I'm still trying to learn
many things of the Prints

00:01:20.530 --> 00:01:24.510 position:56%
and Photographs Division collection,
especially related to architecture,

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:28.010
design, and engineering,
which actually pertains

00:01:28.010 --> 00:01:31.070
to about four million items.

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:36.230
In my early stage of the learning,

00:01:36.230 --> 00:01:39.570
Mr. Vergara's photographs
caught my eye.

00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:43.300
Having a background as
an architecture historian

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:46.310
and as a former resident
of New York City,

00:01:46.310 --> 00:01:50.870
I have been paying attention
to changes in the city.

00:01:50.870 --> 00:01:56.470
When I visited Detroit,
the hometown of my husband,

00:01:56.470 --> 00:02:01.420
in 2007 for the first time,
I was very much fascinated

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:03.620
by the buildings in that city.

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:06.640
Beautiful Art Deco buildings,
and then I couldn't find

00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:11.580
out why the city actually
deteriorated that much.

00:02:11.580 --> 00:02:16.870
Then I got so much interested in
knowing the history of that city.

00:02:16.870 --> 00:02:23.630
Mr. Vergara's photography resonated
with these personal curiosities.

00:02:23.630 --> 00:02:28.130
This summer, when the library
received from Mr. Vergara a series

00:02:28.130 --> 00:02:32.870
of World Trade Center photographs,
I actually caught my breath

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:38.160
for a moment, recalling the time
and the difficulties that I went

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:45.430
through in New York City in 2001
as a new immigrant to this country.

00:02:45.430 --> 00:02:49.970
That became a trigger for
me to host today's event.

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:54.700
This is the first event,
lecture event which I coordinated

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:58.340
as a curator for architecture,
design, and engineering.

00:02:58.340 --> 00:03:01.460
Let me introduce Camilo
a little bit.

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:03.010
&gt;&gt; Sorry, I'm having trouble--

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:04.310
[ Inaudible ]

00:03:04.310 --> 00:03:05.760
[ Laughter ]

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:08.150
&gt;&gt; Mari Nakahara: I hope I don't
have any connection trouble.

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:15.700
[laughs] Camilo Jose Vergara
was born in Chile in 1949

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:21.090
and is a formally trained
sociologist and writer as well

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:25.910
as one of the top documentary
photographers working today.

00:03:25.910 --> 00:03:30.800
His acclaimed books
include Silent Cities:

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:36.050
The Evolution of the
American Cemetery in 1989;

00:03:36.050 --> 00:03:43.910
New American Ghetto in 1995;
American Ruins in 1999;

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:50.660
Twin Towers Remembered, 2001;
Unexpected Chicagoland published

00:03:50.660 --> 00:04:00.860 position:56%
in 2001; Subway Memories in 2004;
How the Other Half Worships in 2005;

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:07.910
Harlem: The Unmarking, Unmaking --
I'm sorry -- of a Ghetto in 2013;

00:04:07.910 --> 00:04:12.970
and Detroit Is No Dry
Bones, published this year,

00:04:12.970 --> 00:04:17.410
which is available for
purchase after this lecture.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:21.340
The website which you are
seeing here, Invincible Cities,

00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:23.510
has made his work better known

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:26.740
through a special map-based
interface.

00:04:26.740 --> 00:04:28.150
I played around a little bit.

00:04:28.150 --> 00:04:30.220
I strongly suggest you do the same.

00:04:30.220 --> 00:04:31.720
It's really interesting.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:33.020
Chronological order.

00:04:33.020 --> 00:04:34.960
The cities and the locations,

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:38.000
you can see how the
city has been changing.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.950
A MacArthur Fellow Genius Award

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:48.180
in 2002 recognized the exceptional
stature of Vergara's work.

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:52.650
In 2013, Vergara became
the first photographer

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:57.040
to receive the president
National Humanities Medal.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:03.070
In 2013, Vergara selected the
Library of Congress, thanks to him,

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:07.500
to be the permanent home for
his photographic archive.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:11.410
Previous acquisition of
Vergara's work were the series

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:16.420
of Silent Cities, which
is documenting cemeteries

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:22.310
across the United States
between 1976 and 1989.

00:05:22.310 --> 00:05:26.900 position:56%
And Twin Towers Remembered, which
is recording that World Trade Center

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:31.600
in New York City between
1970 and in 2001.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:38.030
As of today, approximately 8000
photographs have been transferred

00:05:38.030 --> 00:05:42.560
to the library, and the full
archive is expected to offer

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:50.490
about 10,000 images spanning
the 1970's through the 2010's.

