00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:46.560
So I want to start with the
section from Detroit here,

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:51.970
then show a few pictures of
the World Trade Center series,

00:07:51.970 --> 00:07:54.730
and somewhere along the line,

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:59.200
I will explain how the title
came about that you will see.

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:03.680
So Detroit Is No Dry Bones.

00:08:04.790 --> 00:08:12.870
My first encounter with the city of
Detroit was stepping into a feeling

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:16.870
of unbelief, and it
was unbelief because,

00:08:16.870 --> 00:08:21.010
not that I hadn't seen skyscrapers
before because I had been

00:08:21.010 --> 00:08:26.020
to Chicago, and I had seen them
there, and I had seen briefly

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:31.700
in New York, but I had never
seen an abandoned skyscraper.

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:36.570
And I had never seen 12
abandoned skyscrapers.

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:42.370
[laughs] You know, that
was, what's going on here?

00:08:42.370 --> 00:08:46.940
And, you know, when I asked that
question, I'd take a picture

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:51.190
because I'm kind of slow
in figuring out things,

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:54.450
so I figure I'd take a picture,
and then I'll take another picture,

00:08:54.450 --> 00:09:00.210
and then slowly, you begin to
maybe not figure out how all

00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:06.490
of this came about, but just
have some sense of direction

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:10.590
of what is happening between the
time you first became acquainted

00:09:10.590 --> 00:09:16.380
with it and then the time sort
of you lived off, you know.

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:17.980
That you, you're through.

00:09:17.980 --> 00:09:22.710
You end. I just, I
would look at buildings.

00:09:22.710 --> 00:09:24.670 position:56%
This is the United Artists Building.

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:28.740
The first photograph was a
photograph that was taken

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:31.720
from the hotel that was
at the, at that time,

00:09:31.720 --> 00:09:36.100
was a Salvation Army
building called Harbor Light.

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:37.930
And it was taken in '91.

00:09:37.930 --> 00:09:40.340
That's about 25 years ago.

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:44.660
Building doesn't exist anymore, but
I sort of almost saw that I wanted

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:50.000
to do that, retake that picture
year after year after year,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.150
and then the building
was knocked off.

00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:54.870
And it was, before
that was cinder block,

00:09:54.870 --> 00:09:59.060
so I had to stop, like,
at 2002 or '03.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:05.460
And since then, this whole area
has been revitalized and rebuilt.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:08.760
The whole empty front, you know.

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:13.090
It's not, it's still empty, but
in, within a couple of years,

00:10:13.090 --> 00:10:16.010
all of that's going to,
the picture is going

00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:18.350
to be a completely different one.

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:22.180
Some of the abandoned
buildings, even this one,

00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:25.380
may be rehabilitated someday.

00:10:27.290 --> 00:10:29.550
You would find odd things.

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:36.660
So I decided that one of my
jobs was to sort of keep track

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:39.220
of things that get left out.

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:44.400
So like this man, who
was the caretaker

00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:51.650
of a 32-story skyscraper called
the Broderick Building in Detroit,

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:56.890
and that building, you can see
this, we're on the roof there.

00:10:56.890 --> 00:11:01.840
And he told me at one
time, you know, we were 15.

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:06.890 position:56%
There were 15 people that maintained
this building, and at this point,

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:10.320
must've been around '91, '92.

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:15.920
He was the only one, and
he could, he was not all

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:18.410
that energetic, you
know, at that time.

00:11:18.410 --> 00:11:23.450
So, but every time I went to
Detroit, I would find him,

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:28.990 position:56%
and we would go to the roof, or we'd
stop in different floors and look

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:32.260
around at this collection.

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:40.320
It was this large skyscraper that
you can see in the first picture

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:45.140
that had been left behind.

00:11:45.140 --> 00:11:49.950
People had just left, and there
were lawyers' office, you know,

00:11:49.950 --> 00:11:53.950
where all the archives were
full with stories of divorces,

00:11:53.950 --> 00:12:00.380
and dentists' office that had the
state of the mouth of thousands

00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:02.910
of people because there
were many dentists' office.

00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:07.550
And they had a collection of
equipment, that was ten years old

00:12:07.550 --> 00:12:10.890
or 20 years old, you
know, that was rusting.

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:15.110
And I found that extremely
interesting.

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:21.080
There was also city offices
in some of these buildings

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:23.880
and even records, you know.

00:12:23.880 --> 00:12:26.470
The parole office could
be in a building,

00:12:26.470 --> 00:12:31.020
and then you have all these
parole records left behind.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:34.850
There was a section of Detroit.

00:12:34.850 --> 00:12:39.560
It was like the first wealthy
section that was called Brush Park.

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:41.020
And it was so derelict.

00:12:41.020 --> 00:12:47.300
This is in 1987, and I just
thought there's nothing

00:12:47.300 --> 00:12:52.590 position:56%
that could happen here but this,
it's just going to return to nature.

00:12:52.590 --> 00:12:59.620
It was a house that was, a mansion
that was built by a lumber baron.

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:06.500
Detroit was in a strategic
place, so when the lumber came

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:09.880
from upper Wisconsin, you
know, through the lake,

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:14.230
it would come to Detroit, and
that's what got Detroit started

00:13:14.230 --> 00:13:17.930
in developing a carriage industry.

00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:22.330
First, there were wagons, you
know, and then they, railroad,

00:13:22.330 --> 00:13:30.070
into the railroads, and
finally, into cars, so.

00:13:30.070 --> 00:13:33.400
So here, we're going to see
the evolution of this place.

00:13:33.400 --> 00:13:38.570
This is '91, and you can see
the weeds get even bigger.

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:44.510
You can also see, and
here it's about 2000.

00:13:44.510 --> 00:13:47.210
And that's today.

00:13:47.210 --> 00:13:53.940
And I think the incredible thing
is just not only shows the building

00:13:53.940 --> 00:14:00.130
coming back, it shows how so
much of the, what was built

00:14:00.130 --> 00:14:03.910
around it has disappeared,
is not there anymore.

00:14:03.910 --> 00:14:07.190
And it shows a blonde woman here.

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:10.680
So you can fill in the rest.

00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:17.460
I mean, they used to be first
an area of rooming houses.

00:14:17.460 --> 00:14:22.600
I mean, first an area of
very wealthy people, then it,

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:25.630
they became rooming houses,
and the wealthy people went

00:14:25.630 --> 00:14:30.710
to other neighborhoods
with larger houses.

00:14:30.710 --> 00:14:37.180
Then it was a place for derelicts,
and people who, homeless people,

00:14:37.180 --> 00:14:40.260
and the few people that
sort of hang onto it.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:45.990
And then it's sort of coming back
again as a kind of middle-class,

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:50.460
and in some cases,
upper-class neighborhood.

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:53.630
Well, that one didn't
have the same look.

00:14:53.630 --> 00:14:59.230
This one, for those of you who've
seen Beverly Hill Cops, number,

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:04.060
the cop number one
that was shot in 1984.

00:15:04.060 --> 00:15:08.380
This, you'll see this at the
beginning of the picture.

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:11.520
Well, that's there no more.

00:15:11.520 --> 00:15:13.280
New buildings were built there.

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:14.580
I have the picture.

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:18.640
I'm not showing it here now because
they are, compared to this, I mean,

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:23.400
these were beautiful
buildings that have been lost.

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:29.030
Again, if you get far from the
downtown and you go, in this case,

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:32.980
to the East Side of Detroit,
you see there is a church,

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:38.600 position:56%
and then the churches would organize
these sort of sales of used clothes.

00:15:38.600 --> 00:15:41.760
And here it's all laid
out, you know,

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:45.060
and you can imagine all the coats.

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:49.800
There's hundreds of coats and
those two women selling it.

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:54.430
And I thought of going back and
see what that looked like today.

00:15:54.430 --> 00:15:57.290
I called the church too.

00:15:57.290 --> 00:16:02.340
I wanted to know, I was
very surprised to know,

00:16:02.340 --> 00:16:06.630
find out that they actually
didn't even remember the name

00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:09.170
of the two women there.

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:12.160
You know, so that's what
it looks like today.

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:15.370
This is another set of
two pictures separated

00:16:15.370 --> 00:16:18.540
by about the same number
of years, over 20 years.

00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:20.540
This is the first one.

00:16:20.540 --> 00:16:26.290
Street, it's near Eastern Market
for those of you who know Detroit.

00:16:26.290 --> 00:16:28.730
It's in the East Side too.

00:16:28.730 --> 00:16:34.230
And what you see here,
one of my great interests,

00:16:34.230 --> 00:16:36.170
it's what happens in between.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:37.470
It's the efforts.

00:16:37.470 --> 00:16:43.240
I mean, those places didn't
just sit there and decay,

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:46.120
but there were efforts
from the city to do things.

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:49.730
There were efforts from people
who lived there to do things.

00:16:49.730 --> 00:16:53.870
And I thought it was important
to keep track of those things,

00:16:53.870 --> 00:16:58.060
not just wait until the
whole place was level.

00:16:58.060 --> 00:17:01.640
And so a new population,
new buildings,

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:04.070
new everything came about.

00:17:04.070 --> 00:17:07.430
So here you can see
that at one point,

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:10.360
the city may have put
planters and new trees.

00:17:10.360 --> 00:17:11.660
You see the planters there.

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:15.290
It was big supermarket here.

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:18.550
And this is basically
what it looks like today,

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:21.300
but you still can see
the planters, you know.

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:26.880
So you can do, like, a kind
of an archaeology of places.

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:31.420
This is the Packard Plant,
which is probably the largest

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:40.620
of the car plants there, which is,
at one point during World War II,

00:17:40.620 --> 00:17:42.780
they built airplane engines there.

00:17:42.780 --> 00:17:46.380
They built Rolls-Royce
engines for --

00:17:46.380 --> 00:17:50.670
lots of discoveries were
made there, advances.

00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:54.790
One of them was soundproofing
buildings because they had

00:17:54.790 --> 00:17:59.700
to test these aircraft engines,
which, you know, of course,

00:17:59.700 --> 00:18:04.350
they would render you
deaf in no time.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:09.290
So they had, they did a
lot of insulation also

00:18:09.290 --> 00:18:14.980
because of the temperatures rose
so much, they had special ways

00:18:14.980 --> 00:18:18.440
