00:53:47.720 --> 00:53:50.100
&gt;&gt; [inaudible] apartment buildings?

00:53:50.100 --> 00:53:53.980
Because what happens
if it's a high-rise

00:53:53.980 --> 00:53:59.300
or garden apartment building and
one of the tenants abandons it?

00:53:59.300 --> 00:54:01.070
Then the whole building
disintegrates?

00:54:01.070 --> 00:54:03.140
You kind of showed duplexes,

00:54:03.140 --> 00:54:06.310
but I wonder if it's a big
building, how can you do it?

00:54:06.310 --> 00:54:08.950
&gt;&gt; Camilo Vergara: Well,
there are several pictures

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:13.800
of some big apartment
buildings from Detroit.

00:54:13.800 --> 00:54:16.550
There were some quite
beautiful buildings

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:19.990
and some very large
apartment buildings.

00:54:19.990 --> 00:54:23.700
And it's sort of a slow process,
you know, the disintegration

00:54:23.700 --> 00:54:25.720
of an apartment building.

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:29.210
It's not, it doesn't
happen overnight.

00:54:29.210 --> 00:54:32.890
I mean, sometimes a big fire is,
you know, it just takes care of it.

00:54:32.890 --> 00:54:36.850
I mean, if the roof goes,
there you are, you know.

00:54:36.850 --> 00:54:42.960
So it's, but I do, I follow
many apartment buildings.

00:54:42.960 --> 00:54:45.900
Yeah. So go ahead.

00:54:45.900 --> 00:54:50.890
&gt;&gt; Yes. I'm from Detroit,
although I left there in '72,

00:54:50.890 --> 00:54:57.010
but I still go back to
visit my mother there.

00:54:57.010 --> 00:55:00.100
She'll be 91 next month.

00:55:00.100 --> 00:55:01.400
&gt;&gt; Camilo Vergara: Yeah.

00:55:01.400 --> 00:55:07.140
&gt;&gt; [inaudible] But the old Packard
Building, I worked there the summer

00:55:07.140 --> 00:55:10.110
of '65 as a college student.

00:55:10.110 --> 00:55:14.210
The defense department was there.

00:55:14.210 --> 00:55:23.800
I worked with the defense
department, and I remember going

00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:27.140
from one building to
another building,

00:55:27.140 --> 00:55:29.510
and going through the
abandoned parts

00:55:29.510 --> 00:55:36.380
of the car company,
and how scary it was.

00:55:36.380 --> 00:55:38.340
You would go through
there, and you'd see chassis

00:55:38.340 --> 00:55:42.510
and engines just laying around,
and I would always be looking

00:55:42.510 --> 00:55:44.880
for the rats to come out.

00:55:44.880 --> 00:55:48.290
But it's completely
gone now, like you said.

00:55:48.290 --> 00:55:53.500
Someone has said they're going
to investigate and rebuild it.

00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:59.400
But I don't know if that's
really going to happen.

00:55:59.400 --> 00:56:00.700
&gt;&gt; Camilo Vergara: Yeah, no.

00:56:00.700 --> 00:56:03.040
There were raves at one time.

00:56:03.040 --> 00:56:05.260
You know, they had music inside.

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:13.350
The sort of interesting thing
is that one thing from Detroit

00:56:13.350 --> 00:56:18.810
and from the rest of the country
from the very poor areas is

00:56:18.810 --> 00:56:25.160
that what survives and thrives is
the music that's created there.

00:56:25.160 --> 00:56:27.350
The visuals, not, you know.

00:56:27.350 --> 00:56:31.960 position:56%
It's like, what's inside the
storefront churches that disappears,

00:56:31.960 --> 00:56:36.160
but, you know, we all know
the Supremes, and Motown,

00:56:36.160 --> 00:56:37.930
and techno music, and so on.

00:56:37.930 --> 00:56:39.230
Go ahead.

00:56:39.230 --> 00:56:43.810 position:56%
&gt;&gt; When you started taking photos in
Detroit, did you know you were going

00:56:43.810 --> 00:56:49.320 position:56%
to keep coming back and documenting,
or did that happen later?

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:52.800
Like, when did you decide
these would become series?

00:56:52.800 --> 00:56:56.150
&gt;&gt; Camilo Vergara: Well, you know,
it's partly I think, you know,

00:56:56.150 --> 00:56:59.430
with reference to the ending,
is just that the first picture

00:56:59.430 --> 00:57:02.480
that I take just tries
to be a complete picture

00:57:02.480 --> 00:57:04.890
of whatever's in front of me.

00:57:04.890 --> 00:57:07.920
And then, you know, the picture
is like a question, you know.

00:57:07.920 --> 00:57:10.200
What's going to happen
to this place?

00:57:10.200 --> 00:57:11.920
So, you know, I feel like
I have to go, you know.

00:57:11.920 --> 00:57:16.200 position:56%
So, I mean, you kind of arrange your
finances and you figure, you know,

00:57:16.200 --> 00:57:17.500
who is going to put me up?

00:57:17.500 --> 00:57:19.430
Is somebody going to lend me a car?

00:57:19.430 --> 00:57:21.280
Who is going to, you
know, what I'm going

00:57:21.280 --> 00:57:25.750
to eat, and that sort of thing.

00:57:25.750 --> 00:57:30.290
And then you figure you have
enough money, so you go back.

00:57:30.290 --> 00:57:34.370
And, you know, that's kind
of my way, and I'm very, see,

00:57:34.370 --> 00:57:38.120
I haven't been able to do
Cleveland because, basically,

00:57:38.120 --> 00:57:40.370
there was no base that I
could stay in Cleveland.

00:57:40.370 --> 00:57:41.670
There was no place.

00:57:41.670 --> 00:57:44.890
I would have loved to have
done Cleveland or, you know,

00:57:44.890 --> 00:57:47.500
some of the cities of the South.

00:57:47.500 --> 00:57:48.800
But that's the idea.

00:57:48.800 --> 00:57:54.900
I mean, and I think I've had very
good luck with American historians

00:57:54.900 --> 00:57:57.450
and people interested
in American culture,

00:57:57.450 --> 00:57:59.290
and architecture, and so on.

00:57:59.290 --> 00:58:03.200 position:56%
I've had lousy luck with people who
do art photography and want to show,

00:58:03.200 --> 00:58:05.510
you know, great, their, you
know, moment [phonetic],

00:58:05.510 --> 00:58:10.410
and the National Gallery, and
all those places, you know.

00:58:10.410 --> 00:58:12.010
I've had a couple of places --

00:58:12.010 --> 00:58:15.530
the Getty or some other places
have had a few pictures.

00:58:15.530 --> 00:58:17.140
So it's like a fragmented.

00:58:17.140 --> 00:58:20.470
It's a divided approach to
photography that if you wanted

00:58:20.470 --> 00:58:24.360
to make it as a photographer,
you know,

00:58:24.360 --> 00:58:31.250
all the stuff I'm telling
you is completely irrelevant.

00:58:31.250 --> 00:58:35.560
Why do you want to put for your
